Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.52,0:00:29.55,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.05,0:00:30.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm Ross Dexter.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.48,0:00:31.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm an engineer on the Games
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.19,0:00:32.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Technologies Team at Apple.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.26,0:00:33.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And I'd like to welcome you to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.20,0:00:35.10,Default,,0,0,0,,going beyond 2D with SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.02,0:00:38.39,Default,,0,0,0,,So before we dive in I'd like to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.39,0:00:39.60,Default,,0,0,0,,quickly talk about what
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.60,0:00:41.06,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit is and where it fits
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.06,0:00:42.20,Default,,0,0,0,,in the Apple rendering picture.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.77,0:00:44.49,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit is Apple's 2D graphics
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.49,0:00:45.61,Default,,0,0,0,,framework for games.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.86,0:00:46.49,Default,,0,0,0,,And it's designed to be
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.49,0:00:48.83,Default,,0,0,0,,flexible, fast, and easy to use.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.83,0:00:50.46,Default,,0,0,0,,It's supported across all of our
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.46,0:00:51.93,Default,,0,0,0,,platforms and has an Xcode
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.93,0:00:53.49,Default,,0,0,0,,integrated life editor to make
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.49,0:00:54.90,Default,,0,0,0,,lying out and previewing your
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.90,0:00:56.62,Default,,0,0,0,,game content quick and easy.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.11,0:00:59.88,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit sits along SceneKit or
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.88,0:01:01.33,Default,,0,0,0,,other games oriented graphics
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.33,0:01:02.84,Default,,0,0,0,,framework and both sit on top of
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.84,0:01:03.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.88,0:01:04.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Traditionally they've all been
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.80,0:01:06.16,Default,,0,0,0,,used separately in different
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.16,0:01:06.90,Default,,0,0,0,,contexts.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.44,0:01:09.45,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit for quick and easy 2D,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.45,0:01:10.96,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit as all ready to use 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.96,0:01:12.76,Default,,0,0,0,,engine, and Metal to give you
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.76,0:01:14.24,Default,,0,0,0,,direct access to your devices
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.35,0:01:15.12,Default,,0,0,0,,rendering hardware.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.59,0:01:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead of keeping all three
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.93,0:01:18.77,Default,,0,0,0,,separate we think it's time that
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.77,0:01:20.15,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit breaks out of its 2D
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.15,0:01:20.48,Default,,0,0,0,,mold.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.51,0:01:22.74,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit has a great deal to
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.74,0:01:23.78,Default,,0,0,0,,offer to make using it in
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.78,0:01:24.99,Default,,0,0,0,,combination with SceneKit and
Dialogue: 0,0:01:24.99,0:01:25.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Metal attractive.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.47,0:01:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Since they both use Metal under
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.63,0:01:28.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the hood, it should be trivial
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.85,0:01:30.45,Default,,0,0,0,,to render SpriteKit content in
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.45,0:01:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit or be able to pipe it
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.90,0:01:34.40,Default,,0,0,0,,back into Metal use however you
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.40,0:01:34.81,Default,,0,0,0,,wish.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.05,0:01:37.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Lots of 3D games and apps
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.12,0:01:38.92,Default,,0,0,0,,feature 2D content and SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.92,0:01:40.04,Default,,0,0,0,,provides the perfects means for
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.04,0:01:41.04,Default,,0,0,0,,creating and rendering that
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.04,0:01:41.48,Default,,0,0,0,,content.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.16,0:01:45.76,Default,,0,0,0,,On top of that this year Apple
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.76,0:01:47.22,Default,,0,0,0,,is introducing ARKit, which
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.22,0:01:48.14,Default,,0,0,0,,takes all the hard work out of
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.14,0:01:49.58,Default,,0,0,0,,creating augmented reality apps.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.19,0:01:51.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The addition of this new
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.01,0:01:52.30,Default,,0,0,0,,framework provides one more
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.30,0:01:53.10,Default,,0,0,0,,reason why it's time for
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.10,0:01:55.34,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit to go beyond 2D and
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.34,0:01:56.32,Default,,0,0,0,,into the third dimension.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.95,0:01:57.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And today we're going to show
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.70,0:01:59.39,Default,,0,0,0,,you how to do it and what you
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.80,0:02:02.92,Default,,0,0,0,,can achieve.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.11,0:02:04.53,Default,,0,0,0,,In this session we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.53,0:02:05.89,Default,,0,0,0,,cover how to render SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.89,0:02:07.62,Default,,0,0,0,,content in ARKit, bringing
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.62,0:02:08.41,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit to the world of
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.41,0:02:09.19,Default,,0,0,0,,augmented reality.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.18,0:02:11.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, we'll show you how to get
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.24,0:02:12.41,Default,,0,0,0,,your SpriteKit scenes into
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.41,0:02:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit and how that can
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.95,0:02:15.10,Default,,0,0,0,,improve your augmented reality
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.10,0:02:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,apps.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.23,0:02:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,And then finally we'll introduce
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.38,0:02:18.99,Default,,0,0,0,,you to SKRenderer, which allows
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.99,0:02:20.21,Default,,0,0,0,,you to take more control of how
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.21,0:02:21.97,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit updates and renders.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.37,0:02:25.12,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, let's dive right in
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.12,0:02:26.73,Default,,0,0,0,,with how you can use SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.73,0:02:27.73,Default,,0,0,0,,and ARKit together.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.99,0:02:30.83,Default,,0,0,0,,But first we should talk about
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.83,0:02:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,what augmented reality actually
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.15,0:02:36.49,Default,,0,0,0,,is. Augmented reality combines a
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.57,0:02:38.05,Default,,0,0,0,,real world view with computer
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.05,0:02:38.86,Default,,0,0,0,,rendered content.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.56,0:02:40.59,Default,,0,0,0,,That content gets attached to
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.59,0:02:42.33,Default,,0,0,0,,locations in the real world so
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.33,0:02:43.84,Default,,0,0,0,,that as you move your device and
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.84,0:02:45.34,Default,,0,0,0,,the view shifts, the content
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.34,0:02:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,appears to remain in place.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.45,0:02:49.61,Default,,0,0,0,,That allows you to inspect the
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.61,0:02:51.55,Default,,0,0,0,,content from different angels as
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.55,0:02:52.80,Default,,0,0,0,,if it were a physical object in
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.80,0:02:53.98,Default,,0,0,0,,front of your device.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.61,0:02:55.82,Default,,0,0,0,,And this requires a lot of
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.82,0:02:57.23,Default,,0,0,0,,complex tracking and is a real
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.23,0:02:58.87,Default,,0,0,0,,challenge to implement.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.08,0:03:03.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Thankfully ARKit does all the
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.32,0:03:04.14,Default,,0,0,0,,hard work for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.87,0:03:06.43,Default,,0,0,0,,When you use ARKit it leverages
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.43,0:03:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,your devices camera,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.28,0:03:09.45,Default,,0,0,0,,accelerometer and other hardware
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.64,0:03:11.33,Default,,0,0,0,,to track its position and
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.82,0:03:13.19,Default,,0,0,0,,orientation in the real world.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.59,0:03:14.83,Default,,0,0,0,,All you have to do is provide it
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.83,0:03:15.90,Default,,0,0,0,,the content you want to appear
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.90,0:03:17.91,Default,,0,0,0,,in AR, and ARKit automatically
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.91,0:03:19.32,Default,,0,0,0,,updates the relative positioning
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.43,0:03:20.65,Default,,0,0,0,,of your content as your device
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.65,0:03:21.07,Default,,0,0,0,,moves.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.96,0:03:23.08,Default,,0,0,0,,If you like a deeper dive into
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.08,0:03:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,exactly how this all works, I
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.39,0:03:25.36,Default,,0,0,0,,highly recommend checking out
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.61,0:03:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,the Introducing ARKit session
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.86,0:03:27.89,Default,,0,0,0,,that happened earlier this week.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.53,0:03:31.80,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit is able to track and
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.80,0:03:32.69,Default,,0,0,0,,update the position of your
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.69,0:03:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,content through the use of
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.92,0:03:34.56,Default,,0,0,0,,anchors.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.74,0:03:35.91,Default,,0,0,0,,They are what make AR work.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.60,0:03:39.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Anchors are 3D points that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.31,0:03:40.60,Default,,0,0,0,,correspond to real world
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.60,0:03:42.08,Default,,0,0,0,,features that ARKit detects
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.36,0:03:43.43,Default,,0,0,0,,through Scene and understanding,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.78,0:03:45.36,Default,,0,0,0,,which uses your devices camera
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.36,0:03:47.46,Default,,0,0,0,,to perceive and process the
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.46,0:03:48.53,Default,,0,0,0,,world around you.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.46,0:03:50.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Anchors are easy to create.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.04,0:03:52.61,Default,,0,0,0,,You can request ARKit to detect
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.61,0:03:54.04,Default,,0,0,0,,one at anytime through the API.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.41,0:03:55.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Or you can create one manually
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.70,0:03:57.18,Default,,0,0,0,,using your devices position and
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.18,0:03:57.76,Default,,0,0,0,,orientation.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.09,0:04:01.65,Default,,0,0,0,,So how do we get ARKit working
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.65,0:04:02.51,Default,,0,0,0,,with SpriteKit content?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.80,0:04:05.59,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit is designed to interact
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.59,0:04:06.58,Default,,0,0,0,,directly with SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.29,0:04:08.48,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit will ask that your -- ask
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.55,0:04:09.90,Default,,0,0,0,,your first SpriteKit nodes is
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.90,0:04:11.34,Default,,0,0,0,,attached to anchors and then
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.34,0:04:12.53,Default,,0,0,0,,will automatically position,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.84,0:04:14.74,Default,,0,0,0,,rotate, and scale those nodes as
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.74,0:04:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,the device moves.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.43,0:04:17.95,Default,,0,0,0,,It does this so your SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.95,0:04:19.54,Default,,0,0,0,,content will stay aligned with
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.54,0:04:20.81,Default,,0,0,0,,the anchors giving the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.84,0:04:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,appearance that your content is
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.24,0:04:23.35,Default,,0,0,0,,rooted in the real world.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.67,0:04:25.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprites are rendered so they are
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.60,0:04:26.81,Default,,0,0,0,,always facing the camera.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.91,0:04:28.02,Default,,0,0,0,,So no matter what angle you view
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.02,0:04:30.25,Default,,0,0,0,,them from they're always facing
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.30,0:04:30.66,Default,,0,0,0,,the camera.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.44,0:04:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a technique known as
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.56,0:04:33.58,Default,,0,0,0,,billboarding and it's commonly
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.58,0:04:34.77,Default,,0,0,0,,used in early 3D games.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.47,0:04:37.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So you may not be familiar with
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.53,0:04:38.73,Default,,0,0,0,,how billboarding works, so let's
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.73,0:04:40.36,Default,,0,0,0,,go over a few quick examples of
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.36,0:04:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,how you can use it, it lets you
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.68,0:04:43.17,Default,,0,0,0,,use 2D content in 3D space.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.05,0:04:45.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So say we have sprite position
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.75,0:04:47.19,Default,,0,0,0,,in 3D space and a camera
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.19,0:04:47.69,Default,,0,0,0,,observing it.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.81,0:04:50.32,Default,,0,0,0,,As the camera moves closer to
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.32,0:04:51.45,Default,,0,0,0,,the sprite the sprite grows
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.45,0:04:53.01,Default,,0,0,0,,larger as you'd expect taking
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.01,0:04:53.54,Default,,0,0,0,,more of the view.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.30,0:04:56.52,Default,,0,0,0,,As the camera moves further
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.52,0:04:57.86,Default,,0,0,0,,away, the sprite shrinks.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.88,0:04:59.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I'll rotate the camera.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.58,0:05:03.29,Default,,0,0,0,,As the camera changes its point
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.29,0:05:04.60,Default,,0,0,0,,of view, the sprite continues to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.60,0:05:05.99,Default,,0,0,0,,face the camera at all times.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.67,0:05:07.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And this should be the case from
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.62,0:05:08.58,Default,,0,0,0,,any angle we view it from.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.55,0:05:10.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's add another sprite to our
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.90,0:05:11.96,Default,,0,0,0,,3D scene here to show how this
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.96,0:05:13.69,Default,,0,0,0,,works with multiple 2D objects.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.19,0:05:17.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprites that are further away
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.37,0:05:18.71,Default,,0,0,0,,are rendered behind sprites that
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.71,0:05:19.52,Default,,0,0,0,,are closer to the camera.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.24,0:05:22.62,Default,,0,0,0,,As the camera moves the more
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.62,0:05:24.62,Default,,0,0,0,,distant sprite comes into view.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.16,0:05:27.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Both sprites always face the
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.59,0:05:31.45,Default,,0,0,0,,camera and this simple technique
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.45,0:05:33.17,Default,,0,0,0,,allows your 2D sprite content to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.17,0:05:34.47,Default,,0,0,0,,work in a 3D spaces.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.11,0:05:38.57,Default,,0,0,0,,So now that we've shown you how
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.70,0:05:39.96,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit and SpriteKit work
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.96,0:05:41.92,Default,,0,0,0,,together at a conceptual level,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.96,0:05:43.18,Default,,0,0,0,,let's talk about the actual
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.18,0:05:44.23,Default,,0,0,0,,objects you'll need to implement
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.51,0:05:45.19,Default,,0,0,0,,your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.53,0:05:47.29,Default,,0,0,0,,To work with ARKit and SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.29,0:05:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,there are four important objects
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.57,0:05:49.25,Default,,0,0,0,,for you to know about --
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.12,0:05:51.96,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSession, ARAnchor, ARSKView,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.96,0:05:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,and ARSKViewDelegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.15,0:05:59.10,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSession is the heart of ARKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.10,0:06:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,It handles all the device
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.64,0:06:02.43,Default,,0,0,0,,tracking and orchestrates the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.43,0:06:03.86,Default,,0,0,0,,interactions between ARKit and
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.86,0:06:04.34,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.29,0:06:06.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It has methods for adding and
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.70,0:06:08.45,Default,,0,0,0,,removing anchors that you create
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.45,0:06:08.87,Default,,0,0,0,,in your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.35,0:06:10.85,Default,,0,0,0,,To get started up, you just call
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.85,0:06:12.09,Default,,0,0,0,,the Run method and ARSession
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.09,0:06:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,will began tracking your device.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.07,0:06:16.38,Default,,0,0,0,,You just need to provide it an
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.38,0:06:17.97,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSession Configuration which
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.97,0:06:19.19,Default,,0,0,0,,tells the ARKit which AR
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.19,0:06:20.59,Default,,0,0,0,,techniques it should use.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.06,0:06:22.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So in working with SpriteKit you
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.14,0:06:23.40,Default,,0,0,0,,should just use the AR World
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.40,0:06:24.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Tracking Session Configuration,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.84,0:06:25.63,Default,,0,0,0,,which enables all the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.63,0:06:27.08,Default,,0,0,0,,functionality you'll need from
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.12,0:06:27.58,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.99,0:06:31.55,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit defines real-world
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.55,0:06:33.03,Default,,0,0,0,,features through ARAnchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.49,0:06:34.63,Default,,0,0,0,,It represents a position in the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.63,0:06:35.72,Default,,0,0,0,,real world and contains
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.72,0:06:36.79,Default,,0,0,0,,transform data as well as a
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.79,0:06:37.63,Default,,0,0,0,,unique identifier.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.75,0:06:40.60,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit maps ARAnchors to the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.60,0:06:42.19,Default,,0,0,0,,SKNodes that we provided to
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.19,0:06:45.59,Default,,0,0,0,,render our contents.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.85,0:06:47.14,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit interacts with SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.14,0:06:48.93,Default,,0,0,0,,through ARSKView, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.93,0:06:50.13,Default,,0,0,0,,derived from SKView.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.10,0:06:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,It creates and contains the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.03,0:06:53.35,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSession so you don't need to
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.35,0:06:54.21,Default,,0,0,0,,create it manually.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.21,0:06:55.39,Default,,0,0,0,,And it has methods for getting
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.39,0:06:56.66,Default,,0,0,0,,related anchors and nodes.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.86,0:06:58.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So you need to manually track
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.44,0:06:59.71,Default,,0,0,0,,which node corresponds to what
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.71,0:07:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor and vise versa.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.58,0:07:03.09,Default,,0,0,0,,It also has a hitTest method,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.45,0:07:04.94,Default,,0,0,0,,which is your primary way of
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.94,0:07:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,creating anchors.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.21,0:07:07.25,Default,,0,0,0,,It takes a point on your devices
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.25,0:07:08.74,Default,,0,0,0,,screen and shoots a ray through
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.74,0:07:08.92,Default,,0,0,0,,it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.22,0:07:10.37,Default,,0,0,0,,So looking for the nearest point
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.37,0:07:12.69,Default,,0,0,0,,in the real world for you to
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.69,0:07:15.10,Default,,0,0,0,,attach stuff to.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.55,0:07:16.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, there's
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.39,0:07:17.69,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSKViewDelegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.88,0:07:18.97,Default,,0,0,0,,A protocol derived from
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.97,0:07:20.92,Default,,0,0,0,,SKViewDelegate, which helps you
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.92,0:07:22.13,Default,,0,0,0,,react to anchors being added,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.47,0:07:23.77,Default,,0,0,0,,updated, and removed from the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.77,0:07:24.20,Default,,0,0,0,,session.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.37,0:07:26.57,Default,,0,0,0,,All of its methods are optional
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.68,0:07:27.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and they're the key to using
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.60,0:07:29.16,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit and ARKit together.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.16,0:07:32.17,Default,,0,0,0,,But we'll come back to that in a
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.84,0:07:32.94,Default,,0,0,0,,bit.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.15,0:07:34.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's get started on creating
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.26,0:07:36.02,Default,,0,0,0,,our first ARKit app with
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.02,0:07:36.48,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.50,0:07:39.07,Default,,0,0,0,,First we'll create a new iOS
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.07,0:07:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,project in Xcode.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.28,0:07:42.42,Default,,0,0,0,,You'll see that in Xcode 9,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.50,0:07:43.72,Default,,0,0,0,,there's a new augmented reality
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.72,0:07:47.37,Default,,0,0,0,,app template for you to choose.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.56,0:07:49.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Once you choose the app template
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.34,0:07:50.62,Default,,0,0,0,,to get started with SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.71,0:07:51.68,Default,,0,0,0,,select it as your content
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.68,0:07:52.26,Default,,0,0,0,,technology.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.84,0:07:56.15,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's all there is to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.19,0:07:57.50,Default,,0,0,0,,You're now ready to enter
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.50,0:07:58.31,Default,,0,0,0,,augmented reality.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.33,0:08:00.59,Default,,0,0,0,,The resulting project looks
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.59,0:08:02.06,Default,,0,0,0,,pretty standard for an iOS app,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.06,0:08:03.32,Default,,0,0,0,,but let's go through the files
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.32,0:08:04.01,Default,,0,0,0,,that are important to using
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.01,0:08:05.36,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit and ARKit together.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.43,0:08:09.02,Default,,0,0,0,,First there's Scene.sks.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.06,0:08:11.04,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a standard SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.04,0:08:12.28,Default,,0,0,0,,scene and it's where you create
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.28,0:08:13.74,Default,,0,0,0,,and layout any non-AR content
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.74,0:08:14.60,Default,,0,0,0,,that you want to appear in your
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.60,0:08:14.83,Default,,0,0,0,,app.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.54,0:08:17.11,Default,,0,0,0,,It will act like an overlay for
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.11,0:08:17.98,Default,,0,0,0,,the AR content.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.98,0:08:18.85,Default,,0,0,0,,And so it's useful for things
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.85,0:08:20.35,Default,,0,0,0,,like HUD elements, help text,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.53,0:08:21.09,Default,,0,0,0,,stuff like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.40,0:08:23.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Nodes that have a Z position
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.47,0:08:24.84,Default,,0,0,0,,greater than or equal to 0 will
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.84,0:08:26.77,Default,,0,0,0,,draw over any AR content that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.77,0:08:28.23,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit adds to the scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.10,0:08:30.67,Default,,0,0,0,,All nodes are managed by -- that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.67,0:08:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,are managed by ARKit have Z
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.00,0:08:33.61,Default,,0,0,0,,positions that are less than 0.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.36,0:08:37.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, Scene.swift.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.44,0:08:39.69,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a SpriteKit scene's
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.73,0:08:40.91,Default,,0,0,0,,corresponding source file.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.67,0:08:42.69,Default,,0,0,0,,As with normal SpriteKit apps,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.69,0:08:44.39,Default,,0,0,0,,this is where you put code to
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.42,0:08:46.24,Default,,0,0,0,,manage your scene and Gameplay
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.24,0:08:47.39,Default,,0,0,0,,and logic and is a good place to
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.39,0:08:48.88,Default,,0,0,0,,leverage gameplay kits various
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.88,0:08:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,features.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.99,0:08:53.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And finally we have
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.01,0:08:54.31,Default,,0,0,0,,ViewController.swift.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.81,0:08:56.21,Default,,0,0,0,,The view controller conforms to
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.21,0:08:58.10,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSKViewDelegate and its
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.10,0:08:59.21,Default,,0,0,0,,sceneView property is an
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.24,0:09:00.91,Default,,0,0,0,,instance of ARSKView, which
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.91,0:09:02.21,Default,,0,0,0,,contains the ARSession.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.23,0:09:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,The view controller class is
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.59,0:09:05.46,Default,,0,0,0,,your primary means of
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.46,0:09:06.69,Default,,0,0,0,,interacting with ARKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.40,0:09:08.44,Default,,0,0,0,,In the template it's
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.44,0:09:10.26,Default,,0,0,0,,automatically set up to call run
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.26,0:09:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,on ARSession with an AR World
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.00,0:09:13.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Tracking Session Configuration.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.72,0:09:14.50,Default,,0,0,0,,So you don't need to add it
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.50,0:09:15.01,Default,,0,0,0,,yourself.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.78,0:09:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,This is also where you implement
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.93,0:09:18.22,Default,,0,0,0,,the ARSKView Delegate Methods
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.32,0:09:19.37,Default,,0,0,0,,that are relevant to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.37,0:09:23.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let's talk about the ARKit
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.41,0:09:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Events that the view controller
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.00,0:09:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,would need to react to.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.95,0:09:28.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The first event is when a new
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.55,0:09:30.52,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor gets added to SKSession.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.01,0:09:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,When this happens ARKit will ask
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.52,0:09:34.52,Default,,0,0,0,,the view controller for the
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.52,0:09:35.59,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit nodes you want to
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.59,0:09:37.10,Default,,0,0,0,,associate with an anchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.64,0:09:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So this is when we create our AR
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.44,0:09:39.86,Default,,0,0,0,,content.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.77,0:09:42.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The second event is when an
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.91,0:09:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,existing anchor is updated by
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.88,0:09:45.40,Default,,0,0,0,,the session.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.52,0:09:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,When this occurs ARKit informs a
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.84,0:09:49.80,Default,,0,0,0,,view controller so you can react
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.80,0:09:50.34,Default,,0,0,0,,to the update.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.74,0:09:52.93,Default,,0,0,0,,And the third and final event is
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.93,0:09:54.42,Default,,0,0,0,,when an anchor is removed from
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.42,0:09:54.89,Default,,0,0,0,,the session.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.13,0:09:57.34,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit tells the view controller
Dialogue: 0,0:09:57.34,0:09:58.53,Default,,0,0,0,,so you can form any necessary
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.53,0:09:59.70,Default,,0,0,0,,cleanup in your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.05,0:10:04.90,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSKViewDelegate provides
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.90,0:10:06.02,Default,,0,0,0,,methods tied to each of these
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.02,0:10:06.48,Default,,0,0,0,,events.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.23,0:10:08.60,Default,,0,0,0,,As we mentioned, each of these
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.60,0:10:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,methods is optional so you only
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.68,0:10:11.79,Default,,0,0,0,,need to implement the ones that
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.79,0:10:12.37,Default,,0,0,0,,matter to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.88,0:10:14.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go over each one.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.78,0:10:18.75,Default,,0,0,0,,First is the node for anchor
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.75,0:10:19.14,Default,,0,0,0,,method.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.01,0:10:21.13,Default,,0,0,0,,This gets called when a new
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.13,0:10:22.43,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor is added to the session.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.43,0:10:24.64,Default,,0,0,0,,An ARKit maps that node return
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.64,0:10:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,from this method to the anchor
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.66,0:10:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,that's passed in.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.33,0:10:29.29,Default,,0,0,0,,You should implement this if you
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.29,0:10:30.95,Default,,0,0,0,,want to create a custom node for
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.95,0:10:31.39,Default,,0,0,0,,an anchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:31.51,0:10:33.27,Default,,0,0,0,,If you don't implement the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.27,0:10:35.45,Default,,0,0,0,,method a default empty SKNode is
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.45,0:10:36.71,Default,,0,0,0,,created for you automatically.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.25,0:10:39.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The node that gets returned from
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.20,0:10:40.23,Default,,0,0,0,,this method will be moved,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.51,0:10:42.58,Default,,0,0,0,,rotated, and scaled by ARKit to
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.58,0:10:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,match its anchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.12,0:10:45.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So if you try and make any
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.12,0:10:46.68,Default,,0,0,0,,changes to the transform they'll
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.68,0:10:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,likely be overwritten by ARKit
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.02,0:10:49.17,Default,,0,0,0,,when the device moves.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.12,0:10:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,It's useful to know that any
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.98,0:10:51.98,Default,,0,0,0,,children that are assigned to
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.98,0:10:53.01,Default,,0,0,0,,this node won't have their
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.01,0:10:53.95,Default,,0,0,0,,transforms modified.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.00,0:10:55.49,Default,,0,0,0,,But we'll talk more about this
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.59,0:10:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,with our next method.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.99,0:10:59.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Also know that ARKit
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.04,0:11:00.34,Default,,0,0,0,,automatically adds this node to
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.34,0:11:02.05,Default,,0,0,0,,the scene graph so you don't
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.67,0:11:04.34,Default,,0,0,0,,have to.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.58,0:11:06.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, we have didAdd node for
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.38,0:11:06.69,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.78,0:11:09.08,Default,,0,0,0,,This is called after an SKNode
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.08,0:11:10.44,Default,,0,0,0,,is mapped to an anchor, so after
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.44,0:11:11.92,Default,,0,0,0,,the previous node for anchor
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.92,0:11:13.34,Default,,0,0,0,,method is executed.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.75,0:11:15.90,Default,,0,0,0,,If you implemented the node for
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.90,0:11:17.26,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor method, the node that
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.26,0:11:18.62,Default,,0,0,0,,gets passed in here will be the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.62,0:11:20.13,Default,,0,0,0,,one you returned from there.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.13,0:11:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,If you didn't implement it, it
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.03,0:11:23.29,Default,,0,0,0,,will be a default empty node.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.29,0:11:25.66,Default,,0,0,0,,As we mentioned in the previous
Dialogue: 0,0:11:25.66,0:11:27.18,Default,,0,0,0,,slide the node that's mapped to
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.18,0:11:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,the anchor has it transformed
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.17,0:11:30.09,Default,,0,0,0,,modified ARKit to follow the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.09,0:11:31.40,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor as the device moves.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.34,0:11:33.69,Default,,0,0,0,,As such, if you want to modify
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.69,0:11:34.99,Default,,0,0,0,,the transforms of your content,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.99,0:11:36.33,Default,,0,0,0,,you should add them as children
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.33,0:11:39.12,Default,,0,0,0,,in here as ARKit won't modify
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.50,0:11:41.72,Default,,0,0,0,,them.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.08,0:11:43.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, we'll update node for
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.45,0:11:44.87,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor and didUpdate node for
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.87,0:11:45.17,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.12,0:11:47.37,Default,,0,0,0,,These methods are called before
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.37,0:11:48.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and after the node is updated
Dialogue: 0,0:11:48.91,0:11:49.95,Default,,0,0,0,,with a given anchors data.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.06,0:11:52.32,Default,,0,0,0,,True to their names willUpdate
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.32,0:11:53.43,Default,,0,0,0,,node for anchor is called before
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.43,0:11:55.02,Default,,0,0,0,,the update, and didUpdate node
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.07,0:11:56.12,Default,,0,0,0,,for anchor is called after the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.12,0:11:56.49,Default,,0,0,0,,update.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.40,0:11:58.25,Default,,0,0,0,,This occurs when the device
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.25,0:11:59.74,Default,,0,0,0,,moves and the view changes.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.82,0:12:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The nodes position, rotation,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.00,0:12:03.05,Default,,0,0,0,,and or scale is subject to
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.05,0:12:04.56,Default,,0,0,0,,change between calls to these
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.56,0:12:04.92,Default,,0,0,0,,methods.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.16,0:12:09.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, didRemove node for
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.99,0:12:10.33,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.20,0:12:12.32,Default,,0,0,0,,This gets called the node is
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.32,0:12:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,removed from the scene graph,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.98,0:12:15.50,Default,,0,0,0,,which occurs when its course on
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.50,0:12:16.80,Default,,0,0,0,,the anchor is removed from
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.80,0:12:17.34,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSession.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.76,0:12:19.83,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, that covers the
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.83,0:12:21.34,Default,,0,0,0,,important parts of the API.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.34,0:12:23.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's take a look at some code.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.00,0:12:24.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's cover creating an
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.83,0:12:25.19,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.56,0:12:27.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Here we're looking at a handler
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.21,0:12:28.29,Default,,0,0,0,,for the touches began event.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.96,0:12:33.22,Default,,0,0,0,,When the device reports a touch,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.22,0:12:34.52,Default,,0,0,0,,we get the location of the touch
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.59,0:12:35.94,Default,,0,0,0,,in our ARSKView.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.63,0:12:39.95,Default,,0,0,0,,We then provide the touch
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.95,0:12:42.56,Default,,0,0,0,,location to the ARSKView's hit
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.56,0:12:44.38,Default,,0,0,0,,test method, which shoots a ray
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.38,0:12:45.90,Default,,0,0,0,,out into the real world looking
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.90,0:12:47.13,Default,,0,0,0,,for feature points that we can
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.13,0:12:48.35,Default,,0,0,0,,turn into anchors.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.37,0:12:50.63,Default,,0,0,0,,It returns an array of all the
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.63,0:12:52.32,Default,,0,0,0,,hits that it registers sorted
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.32,0:12:53.69,Default,,0,0,0,,from nearest to furthest.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.69,0:12:58.63,Default,,0,0,0,,We take the nearest hit and we
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.63,0:13:00.01,Default,,0,0,0,,use this world transform to
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.01,0:13:02.06,Default,,0,0,0,,create and ARAnchor, which we
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.06,0:13:02.90,Default,,0,0,0,,then add to the session.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.90,0:13:05.61,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's all there is to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.61,0:13:06.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Creating anchors could not be
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.79,0:13:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,simpler.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.32,0:13:12.25,Default,,0,0,0,,So now that we've added a new
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.25,0:13:13.51,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor to the session, the
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.51,0:13:14.44,Default,,0,0,0,,session will ask the view
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.44,0:13:15.61,Default,,0,0,0,,controller for the SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.61,0:13:16.62,Default,,0,0,0,,content that we want to attach
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.62,0:13:17.73,Default,,0,0,0,,to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.12,0:13:21.39,Default,,0,0,0,,To do this we've implemented
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.39,0:13:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSKView Delegates didAdd node
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.00,0:13:23.77,Default,,0,0,0,,for anchor method.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.65,0:13:26.07,Default,,0,0,0,,We haven't implemented node for
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.07,0:13:27.56,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor, so default empty node
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.56,0:13:28.75,Default,,0,0,0,,was created for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.99,0:13:29.69,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's [inaudible] of this
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.93,0:13:30.61,Default,,0,0,0,,method.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.41,0:13:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,So now all we need to do is
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.48,0:13:35.43,Default,,0,0,0,,create the content we want to
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.43,0:13:37.76,Default,,0,0,0,,attach to the anchor and then
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.82,0:13:40.55,Default,,0,0,0,,add it as a child of the node
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.55,0:13:41.59,Default,,0,0,0,,that's passed into this method.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.59,0:13:43.85,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit will automatically update
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.85,0:13:45.24,Default,,0,0,0,,the node so that it will follow
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.24,0:13:46.59,Default,,0,0,0,,the anchor as the device moves
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.88,0:13:47.82,Default,,0,0,0,,so you don't need to do anything
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.82,0:13:48.19,Default,,0,0,0,,else.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.19,0:13:52.15,Default,,0,0,0,,So now that we've shown you
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.15,0:13:53.82,Default,,0,0,0,,exactly how to use the ARKit API
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.82,0:13:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,with SpriteKit, let's enter
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.20,0:13:57.27,Default,,0,0,0,,augmented reality.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.52,0:14:07.55,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.05,0:14:10.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's open our app here.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.13,0:14:12.45,Default,,0,0,0,,So we see we're doing our video
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.45,0:14:13.27,Default,,0,0,0,,pass through now.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.27,0:14:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,We can see our lovely audience
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.20,0:14:15.66,Default,,0,0,0,,out there.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.99,0:14:17.05,Default,,0,0,0,,You're all famous now.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.05,0:14:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's start placing some
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.46,0:14:20.96,Default,,0,0,0,,content in augmented reality.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.55,0:14:23.79,Default,,0,0,0,,As I tap on my screen I'm
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.60,0:14:28.28,Default,,0,0,0,,placing content half a meter out
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.28,0:14:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,in front of me.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.72,0:14:30.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Here I'm just placing
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.83,0:14:32.86,Default,,0,0,0,,SKLabelNode's with Emoji.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.01,0:14:34.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Fun fact -- you can use emoji in
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.90,0:14:35.79,Default,,0,0,0,,your SpriteKit apps by just
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.79,0:14:36.45,Default,,0,0,0,,using labels.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.56,0:14:37.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Just paste them in there.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.42,0:14:39.45,Default,,0,0,0,,And you see they have them
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.58,0:14:40.89,Default,,0,0,0,,floating in 3D space.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.89,0:14:43.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And as I move the camera around
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.54,0:14:46.80,Default,,0,0,0,,they move relative to one
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.80,0:14:47.14,Default,,0,0,0,,another.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.72,0:14:50.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Just placing them in space is a
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.20,0:14:50.94,Default,,0,0,0,,little boring.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.94,0:14:52.93,Default,,0,0,0,,I can also place them on a
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.93,0:14:53.51,Default,,0,0,0,,surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.75,0:14:57.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And it will detect intersection
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.43,0:14:59.76,Default,,0,0,0,,with the surface with the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.76,0:15:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,HitTest method that we were
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.66,0:15:01.57,Default,,0,0,0,,talking about before.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.57,0:15:06.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And then it places the emoji on
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.28,0:15:07.53,Default,,0,0,0,,the surface of the table that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.53,0:15:08.03,Default,,0,0,0,,it's detected.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.67,0:15:10.64,Default,,0,0,0,,But placing emoji is just a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.64,0:15:11.79,Default,,0,0,0,,little boring.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.09,0:15:13.30,Default,,0,0,0,,So now we're going to switch
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.30,0:15:16.68,Default,,0,0,0,,into blasting mode and then we
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.68,0:15:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,can blow up our emoji, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.17,0:15:20.30,Default,,0,0,0,,a little bit more fun.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.49,0:15:23.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Also pay attention to the text
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.55,0:15:25.22,Default,,0,0,0,,in our -- in the lower left hand
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.22,0:15:27.79,Default,,0,0,0,,corner here and the way that our
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.79,0:15:31.15,Default,,0,0,0,,emoji are flipping around when
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.15,0:15:32.65,Default,,0,0,0,,we destroy them, because that's
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.73,0:15:33.82,Default,,0,0,0,,going to become relevant in a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.82,0:15:34.17,Default,,0,0,0,,moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.93,0:15:37.26,Default,,0,0,0,,So you see how easy it is to
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.26,0:15:41.16,Default,,0,0,0,,quickly create an app and use a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.16,0:15:43.35,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content to enter
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.35,0:15:44.06,Default,,0,0,0,,augmented realty.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.27,0:15:45.39,Default,,0,0,0,,This is just a slightly tweaked
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.39,0:15:47.74,Default,,0,0,0,,version of the template app that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:47.74,0:15:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,you can create right now using
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.42,0:15:50.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode 9.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.24,0:15:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's SpriteKit with ARKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.52,0:15:58.70,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:15:59.20,0:16:00.32,Default,,0,0,0,,So you see how easy it is to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.32,0:16:01.32,Default,,0,0,0,,enter augmented reality when
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.32,0:16:02.55,Default,,0,0,0,,using ARKit and SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.55,0:16:02.94,Default,,0,0,0,,together.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.75,0:16:04.82,Default,,0,0,0,,As I mentioned there are a few
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.82,0:16:06.02,Default,,0,0,0,,other SpriteKit features in
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.02,0:16:06.95,Default,,0,0,0,,there, some of which that were
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.95,0:16:07.93,Default,,0,0,0,,present in the demo that I'd
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.93,0:16:08.72,Default,,0,0,0,,like to quickly cover.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.06,0:16:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So hopefully you notice the text
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.00,0:16:13.16,Default,,0,0,0,,on the bottom of our screen in
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.16,0:16:14.32,Default,,0,0,0,,the demo app animating.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.76,0:16:15.94,Default,,0,0,0,,This was done with a single
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.99,0:16:17.31,Default,,0,0,0,,SKLabelNode, thanks to the fact
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.31,0:16:18.59,Default,,0,0,0,,that they now support attributed
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.59,0:16:19.03,Default,,0,0,0,,strings.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.15,0:16:21.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Attributed strings allows you to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.10,0:16:23.38,Default,,0,0,0,,specify the attributes of each
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.38,0:16:25.03,Default,,0,0,0,,character in a string, letting
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.03,0:16:26.21,Default,,0,0,0,,you mix things like different
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.21,0:16:27.95,Default,,0,0,0,,colors and fonts in the same
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.95,0:16:28.33,Default,,0,0,0,,label.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.33,0:16:30.86,Default,,0,0,0,,It uses NSAAttributedString and
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.86,0:16:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,all you have to do is set it on
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.98,0:16:34.23,Default,,0,0,0,,SKLabelNodes new attributedText
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.23,0:16:34.67,Default,,0,0,0,,property.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.00,0:16:38.82,Default,,0,0,0,,The emoji in our augmented
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.82,0:16:40.03,Default,,0,0,0,,reality apps spun about in ways
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.03,0:16:41.28,Default,,0,0,0,,that weren't possible until now
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.28,0:16:42.32,Default,,0,0,0,,thanks to the new
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.32,0:16:43.10,Default,,0,0,0,,SKTransformNode.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.56,0:16:46.89,Default,,0,0,0,,SKNode already had z rotation,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.75,0:16:49.18,Default,,0,0,0,,but SKTransformNode adds the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.18,0:16:50.44,Default,,0,0,0,,ability for you to rotate around
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.44,0:16:52.33,Default,,0,0,0,,the x and y-axis as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.10,0:16:54.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Aligned for full 3D rotations
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.65,0:16:55.71,Default,,0,0,0,,for SpriteKit content.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.53,0:16:58.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And these rotations apply to all
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.12,0:16:59.01,Default,,0,0,0,,child nodes as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.01,0:17:01.74,Default,,0,0,0,,SKTransformNode uses
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.74,0:17:02.96,Default,,0,0,0,,orthographic projection.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.26,0:17:04.21,Default,,0,0,0,,So it doesn't apply any
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.27,0:17:05.32,Default,,0,0,0,,perspective skewing to your
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.32,0:17:05.85,Default,,0,0,0,,nodes.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.74,0:17:08.16,Default,,0,0,0,,You can specify your rotations
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.16,0:17:10.11,Default,,0,0,0,,through the x, y, and z rotation
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.11,0:17:11.71,Default,,0,0,0,,properties or you can use a
Dialogue: 0,0:17:11.71,0:17:12.87,Default,,0,0,0,,specialized getters and setters
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.87,0:17:14.61,Default,,0,0,0,,for Euler angles, rotation
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.81,0:17:18.19,Default,,0,0,0,,matrices, and quaternions.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.62,0:17:19.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, on the ender side of
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.68,0:17:20.86,Default,,0,0,0,,things, SpriteKit is fully
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.86,0:17:22.77,Default,,0,0,0,,compatible with Xcode's View
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.77,0:17:23.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.18,0:17:25.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It displays the entire scene
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.42,0:17:26.80,Default,,0,0,0,,graph and gives you the neat
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.80,0:17:28.48,Default,,0,0,0,,exploded 3D view of your scene,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.81,0:17:29.93,Default,,0,0,0,,which can be a great help when
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.93,0:17:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,you're trying to debug layout --
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.68,0:17:33.18,Default,,0,0,0,,content layout issues.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.42,0:17:34.73,Default,,0,0,0,,It also allows you to inspect
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.73,0:17:35.95,Default,,0,0,0,,all of your node properties so
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.29,0:17:37.10,Default,,0,0,0,,you can see the state of
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.10,0:17:38.03,Default,,0,0,0,,everything in your scene as the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.03,0:17:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,moment the app was paused.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.56,0:17:40.84,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a really great new
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.84,0:17:41.82,Default,,0,0,0,,feature, so please check out the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.82,0:17:43.14,Default,,0,0,0,,debugging with Xcode 9 session
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.14,0:17:44.73,Default,,0,0,0,,for more information on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.36,0:17:48.12,Default,,0,0,0,,We've shown you how quick and
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.12,0:17:49.98,Default,,0,0,0,,easy it is to get started with
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.98,0:17:51.74,Default,,0,0,0,,using ARKit and SpriteKit to
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.74,0:17:53.26,Default,,0,0,0,,create an augmented reality app.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.21,0:17:55.59,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit handles all of the hard
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.59,0:17:56.92,Default,,0,0,0,,parts of augmented reality for
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.92,0:17:58.64,Default,,0,0,0,,you and SpriteKit makes
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.64,0:17:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,rendering content a snap.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.61,0:18:02.40,Default,,0,0,0,,We've also introduced new
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.40,0:18:03.57,Default,,0,0,0,,features to SpriteKit that give
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.57,0:18:04.72,Default,,0,0,0,,you greater flexibility in
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.72,0:18:05.91,Default,,0,0,0,,developing your apps and give
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.91,0:18:07.21,Default,,0,0,0,,you new options for debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.21,0:18:08.04,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.73,0:18:12.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But you may have a few lingering
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.12,0:18:12.79,Default,,0,0,0,,questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.20,0:18:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,What if we don't want
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.04,0:18:15.07,Default,,0,0,0,,billboarded sprites?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.64,0:18:16.74,Default,,0,0,0,,What if we want our SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.74,0:18:17.64,Default,,0,0,0,,content to be effective by
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.64,0:18:18.16,Default,,0,0,0,,perspective?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.16,0:18:21.89,Default,,0,0,0,,What if we want to mix 2D and 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.13,0:18:23.60,Default,,0,0,0,,content in augmented reality?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.29,0:18:26.24,Default,,0,0,0,,What if wanted to take SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.24,0:18:27.22,Default,,0,0,0,,further into 3D?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.06,0:18:31.19,Default,,0,0,0,,The answer lies in combining
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.19,0:18:33.24,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit, SpriteKit, and ARKit
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.54,0:18:36.21,Default,,0,0,0,,all at once.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.74,0:18:38.29,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit and SpriteKit's 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.29,0:18:40.05,Default,,0,0,0,,counterpart, it's a ready to use
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.08,0:18:41.63,Default,,0,0,0,,3D engine with it's own Xcode
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.63,0:18:42.87,Default,,0,0,0,,integrated live editor.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.87,0:18:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,What you may not know is that
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.96,0:18:47.58,Default,,0,0,0,,you can use SpriteKit Scenes as
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.58,0:18:49.30,Default,,0,0,0,,the material on geometry in
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.30,0:18:49.88,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.80,0:18:51.56,Default,,0,0,0,,That allows you to render
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.56,0:18:53.33,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content with complex
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.33,0:18:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,3D transforms and perspective
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.94,0:18:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,effect.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:56.31,0:18:57.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Additionally you can easily mix
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.73,0:18:59.51,Default,,0,0,0,,2D SpriteKit content with 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.94,0:19:04.18,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit content in the same
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.26,0:19:04.51,Default,,0,0,0,,context.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.94,0:19:06.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Like SpriteKit, SceneKit is also
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.33,0:19:08.48,Default,,0,0,0,,integrated with ARKit, creating
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.48,0:19:10.46,Default,,0,0,0,,a project that uses SceneKit in
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.46,0:19:12.29,Default,,0,0,0,,an augmented reality app is the
Dialogue: 0,0:19:12.29,0:19:13.35,Default,,0,0,0,,same as with SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.30,0:19:15.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Just change the content
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.38,0:19:16.70,Default,,0,0,0,,technology to SceneKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.15,0:19:21.39,Default,,0,0,0,,The API is designed to be very
Dialogue: 0,0:19:21.39,0:19:22.44,Default,,0,0,0,,similar to the one you use with
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.44,0:19:22.91,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.20,0:19:24.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Only the names of few objects
Dialogue: 0,0:19:25.46,0:19:27.50,Default,,0,0,0,,are different.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:27.50,0:19:30.23,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSKView becomes ARSCNView and
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.23,0:19:31.73,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSKViewDelegate becomes
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.79,0:19:32.94,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSCNViewDelegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.86,0:19:34.87,Default,,0,0,0,,As with SpriteKit the template
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.90,0:19:37.03,Default,,0,0,0,,creates ARSCNView for you and
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.03,0:19:38.61,Default,,0,0,0,,the ViewController conforms to
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.61,0:19:39.64,Default,,0,0,0,,ARSCNViewDelegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.38,0:19:41.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Now in the interest in brevity
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.60,0:19:42.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and because the API is so
Dialogue: 0,0:19:42.46,0:19:43.42,Default,,0,0,0,,similar, we won't bother
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.42,0:19:44.19,Default,,0,0,0,,covering the rest here.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:44.89,0:19:48.36,Default,,0,0,0,,So next we want to get out
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.36,0:19:49.60,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content rendering
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.60,0:19:50.66,Default,,0,0,0,,within a SceneKit scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.60,0:19:53.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Normally with SpriteKit you have
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.23,0:19:54.82,Default,,0,0,0,,your scene and you set it on an
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.82,0:19:55.30,Default,,0,0,0,,SKView.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.26,0:19:58.41,Default,,0,0,0,,SKView then works with UIKit or
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.41,0:20:00.39,Default,,0,0,0,,AppKit on Mac OS to get your
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.39,0:20:03.24,Default,,0,0,0,,content on screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.05,0:20:04.89,Default,,0,0,0,,To get your content rendering in
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.04,0:20:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit things are handled a
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.34,0:20:07.08,Default,,0,0,0,,little differently.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.73,0:20:08.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead of setting your scene on
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.86,0:20:10.41,Default,,0,0,0,,the view, you set it on the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.41,0:20:11.99,Default,,0,0,0,,material property of the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:11.99,0:20:13.06,Default,,0,0,0,,geometry on which you want the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.06,0:20:14.91,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content to appear.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.91,0:20:17.34,Default,,0,0,0,,And then that material works
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.34,0:20:18.79,Default,,0,0,0,,with SceneKit to render you
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.79,0:20:20.35,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content and then
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.35,0:20:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,texture map it onto the geometry
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.12,0:20:23.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the material is associated with.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.46,0:20:27.57,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's go over a few examples
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.57,0:20:29.09,Default,,0,0,0,,of rendering SpriteKit content
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.21,0:20:30.43,Default,,0,0,0,,on SceneKit Geometry.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.31,0:20:32.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Here was have a basic SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:20:32.86,0:20:33.23,Default,,0,0,0,,scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.83,0:20:35.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And here's what we get when we
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.87,0:20:37.43,Default,,0,0,0,,render that on a scene on a
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.43,0:20:39.23,Default,,0,0,0,,plane in scene kit.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.00,0:20:42.61,Default,,0,0,0,,We also apply the SpriteKit's
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.61,0:20:45.37,Default,,0,0,0,,scene to a cube or even a
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.37,0:20:45.77,Default,,0,0,0,,sphere.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.86,0:20:47.29,Default,,0,0,0,,You can use it just like a
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.29,0:20:48.76,Default,,0,0,0,,regular texture and the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.76,0:20:49.91,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit -- as the SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.91,0:20:51.42,Default,,0,0,0,,scene updates, your texture will
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.42,0:20:52.91,Default,,0,0,0,,be updated along with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:54.54,0:20:56.23,Default,,0,0,0,,So now I'd like to quickly show
Dialogue: 0,0:20:56.23,0:20:57.48,Default,,0,0,0,,you how easy it is to use
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.48,0:20:58.86,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit with SceneKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.99,0:21:03.06,Default,,0,0,0,,First, get the SpriteKit scene
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.06,0:21:04.32,Default,,0,0,0,,that you want to use in
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.32,0:21:04.77,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.37,0:21:08.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, create the geometry you
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.77,0:21:09.86,Default,,0,0,0,,want the SpriteKit scene to be
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.86,0:21:10.36,Default,,0,0,0,,rendered on.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.09,0:21:12.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Here we're creating a simple
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.25,0:21:12.69,Default,,0,0,0,,plane.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.42,0:21:16.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Then you just need to set the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.47,0:21:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit scene as the contents
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.00,0:21:19.56,Default,,0,0,0,,of the diffuse property of the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.56,0:21:20.39,Default,,0,0,0,,planes material.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.36,0:21:22.73,Default,,0,0,0,,That will cause the SceneKit to
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.73,0:21:23.77,Default,,0,0,0,,render the SpriteKit Scene to a
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.77,0:21:25.50,Default,,0,0,0,,texture and then apply it to the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.50,0:21:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,geometry.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.00,0:21:30.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Here we're setting the material
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.69,0:21:31.80,Default,,0,0,0,,to be double-sided.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.29,0:21:33.42,Default,,0,0,0,,This causes the SpriteKit Scene
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.42,0:21:34.76,Default,,0,0,0,,to appear on both sides of the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.76,0:21:35.16,Default,,0,0,0,,plane.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.79,0:21:38.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Then we just need to create a
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.87,0:21:40.20,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit node for the plane and
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.20,0:21:44.15,Default,,0,0,0,,add it to the SceneKit scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:44.70,0:21:45.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Now the plane will show up in
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.61,0:21:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,the scene with the contents of
Dialogue: 0,0:21:46.72,0:21:48.16,Default,,0,0,0,,your SpriteKit scene texture
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.16,0:21:49.75,Default,,0,0,0,,mapped onto it.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.24,0:21:53.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So now I'd like to show you demo
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.18,0:21:54.23,Default,,0,0,0,,of some of the things you can do
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.23,0:21:55.26,Default,,0,0,0,,when you use SpriteKit and
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.26,0:21:56.75,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit together with ARKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.52,0:22:08.04,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.54,0:22:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:11.22,0:22:13.48,Default,,0,0,0,,So here I have a demo that I've
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.48,0:22:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,built on top of the sample code
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.55,0:22:18.04,Default,,0,0,0,,that ARKit has released, that
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.04,0:22:19.29,Default,,0,0,0,,you can find to their session
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.29,0:22:19.77,Default,,0,0,0,,website.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.77,0:22:23.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And here I just is detecting a
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.01,0:22:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,plane for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.41,0:22:27.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Now if I tap on the screen it
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.12,0:22:29.70,Default,,0,0,0,,places a SpriteKit scene for us
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.70,0:22:30.42,Default,,0,0,0,,in the world here.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.58,0:22:32.67,Default,,0,0,0,,And you see that this a fully
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.67,0:22:34.17,Default,,0,0,0,,live SpriteKit scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.17,0:22:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,You see the trees are animating.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.35,0:22:38.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And in fact I can actually
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.94,0:22:40.29,Default,,0,0,0,,interact with this directly.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:40.33,0:22:41.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, here let's actually --
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.80,0:22:44.35,Default,,0,0,0,,let's blow it up a little bit.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.35,0:22:45.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Since we are in 3D we can do all
Dialogue: 0,0:22:45.76,0:22:46.54,Default,,0,0,0,,kinds of cool things.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.54,0:22:48.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We can move this guy around, we
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.70,0:22:51.29,Default,,0,0,0,,can rotate, and we can scale,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:51.29,0:22:53.22,Default,,0,0,0,,make it a little bigger.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.06,0:22:55.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So now I can actually interact
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.79,0:22:56.73,Default,,0,0,0,,with this scene directly.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.73,0:22:58.69,Default,,0,0,0,,I have controls on my device
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.69,0:23:00.99,Default,,0,0,0,,here, I can move my character
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.99,0:23:03.17,Default,,0,0,0,,around, you can jump around.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.48,0:23:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Hard to get over that thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.70,0:23:07.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. And so we can jump around
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.82,0:23:09.58,Default,,0,0,0,,in real time, interact with this
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.58,0:23:10.72,Default,,0,0,0,,just like a normal SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.72,0:23:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,scene rendered in 3D.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:13.86,0:23:15.24,Default,,0,0,0,,But just having it sit here on
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.24,0:23:16.89,Default,,0,0,0,,the surface is a little boring.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.09,0:23:17.99,Default,,0,0,0,,We should do something a little
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.99,0:23:19.08,Default,,0,0,0,,more interesting, it a little
Dialogue: 0,0:23:19.08,0:23:19.94,Default,,0,0,0,,more 3D.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.34,0:23:21.47,Default,,0,0,0,,So if I actually touch this
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.47,0:23:24.05,Default,,0,0,0,,button up here, the scene flips
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.05,0:23:26.40,Default,,0,0,0,,up and --
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.52,0:23:30.58,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.08,0:23:32.95,Default,,0,0,0,,If I touch it again it separates
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.95,0:23:34.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the different layers that I have
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.15,0:23:34.44,Default,,0,0,0,,in here.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.44,0:23:35.57,Default,,0,0,0,,So we don't actually have just
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.61,0:23:36.71,Default,,0,0,0,,one SpriteKit scene --
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.52,0:23:40.55,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:23:41.05,0:23:41.71,Default,,0,0,0,,We actually have three
Dialogue: 0,0:23:41.71,0:23:42.71,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit's scenes here, one for
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.71,0:23:43.28,Default,,0,0,0,,each layer here.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.28,0:23:44.87,Default,,0,0,0,,One for the middle -- front,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.87,0:23:46.14,Default,,0,0,0,,middle, and background.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.62,0:23:49.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So this shows you the kind of
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.44,0:23:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,stuff that you can do when you
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.55,0:23:51.76,Default,,0,0,0,,use SpriteKit and SceneKit
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.76,0:23:54.35,Default,,0,0,0,,together with ARKit but maybe
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.35,0:23:55.37,Default,,0,0,0,,you start to feel a little
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.37,0:23:58.34,Default,,0,0,0,,constrained by the level here.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:59.15,0:24:00.36,Default,,0,0,0,,And maybe we want to have our
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.36,0:24:02.18,Default,,0,0,0,,little guy go out on an
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.18,0:24:02.95,Default,,0,0,0,,adventure on his own.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.12,0:24:03.91,Default,,0,0,0,,He can run out into the real
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.91,0:24:04.39,Default,,0,0,0,,world here.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.66,0:24:06.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh this button looks kind of
Dialogue: 0,0:24:06.58,0:24:07.06,Default,,0,0,0,,tempting.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.45,0:24:11.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Yay.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.52,0:24:18.56,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.06,0:24:19.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So that gives you an idea of
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.83,0:24:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,what you can do when you use
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.74,0:24:22.61,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit in a 3D context with
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.61,0:24:24.59,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit together with ARKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.31,0:24:28.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So as you saw using SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.95,0:24:30.16,Default,,0,0,0,,with SceneKit allows for full 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:24:30.16,0:24:31.46,Default,,0,0,0,,transforms and perspective,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.76,0:24:32.44,Default,,0,0,0,,which allows you to do some
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.44,0:24:33.22,Default,,0,0,0,,pretty neat things.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.84,0:24:35.38,Default,,0,0,0,,It allows you to mix 2D and 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.38,0:24:36.93,Default,,0,0,0,,content within the same context
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.52,0:24:38.93,Default,,0,0,0,,and it's fully compatible with
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.93,0:24:41.12,Default,,0,0,0,,the ARKit and it works great in
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.12,0:24:42.29,Default,,0,0,0,,general 3D apps as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:42.29,0:24:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,So now that we've covered how to
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.56,0:24:48.18,Default,,0,0,0,,work with ARKit and SceneKit, I
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.18,0:24:49.11,Default,,0,0,0,,would like to introduce you to a
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.11,0:24:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,another new SpriteKit feature --
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.09,0:24:51.98,Default,,0,0,0,,SKRenderer.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.14,0:24:56.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's talk a bit about how
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.06,0:24:57.50,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit works under the hood.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.38,0:24:59.01,Default,,0,0,0,,As we've mentioned in the
Dialogue: 0,0:24:59.01,0:25:00.80,Default,,0,0,0,,previous section, with normal
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.80,0:25:02.05,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit Rendering you have
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.05,0:25:03.62,Default,,0,0,0,,your scene and you set it on an
Dialogue: 0,0:25:03.62,0:25:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,SKView, which then works with
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.57,0:25:07.74,Default,,0,0,0,,UIKit and AppKit to get your
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.74,0:25:09.05,Default,,0,0,0,,content on the screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:10.30,0:25:11.35,Default,,0,0,0,,SKView handles all of the
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.35,0:25:12.83,Default,,0,0,0,,updating and rendering for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.93,0:25:14.80,Default,,0,0,0,,The upside of this is that it
Dialogue: 0,0:25:14.80,0:25:15.91,Default,,0,0,0,,makes it very easy to get
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.91,0:25:16.83,Default,,0,0,0,,started with SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.74,0:25:18.67,Default,,0,0,0,,But what if you want to render
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.67,0:25:20.26,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content in a 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.26,0:25:20.78,Default,,0,0,0,,context?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.52,0:25:24.28,Default,,0,0,0,,One solution as we showed you is
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.55,0:25:26.31,Default,,0,0,0,,to use SpriteKit with SceneKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:26.81,0:25:28.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead of setting your scene on
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.36,0:25:29.59,Default,,0,0,0,,the view, you use it as a
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.59,0:25:31.06,Default,,0,0,0,,material in SceneKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:31.94,0:25:33.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And this let's you do all kinds
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.01,0:25:33.62,Default,,0,0,0,,of cool stuff.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.62,0:25:35.98,Default,,0,0,0,,But when SpriteKit updates and
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.98,0:25:37.23,Default,,0,0,0,,renders is still out of your
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.23,0:25:37.80,Default,,0,0,0,,hands.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:38.80,0:25:40.90,Default,,0,0,0,,What if you want more control?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:41.44,0:25:42.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe you want to update with
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.42,0:25:45.40,Default,,0,0,0,,exact fixed time steps or update
Dialogue: 0,0:25:45.40,0:25:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,without rendering or render
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.76,0:25:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,without updating or update once
Dialogue: 0,0:25:48.87,0:25:50.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and render twice, each time from
Dialogue: 0,0:25:50.35,0:25:51.08,Default,,0,0,0,,a different viewpoint.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.29,0:25:53.60,Default,,0,0,0,,What if we wanted to work
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.60,0:25:56.19,Default,,0,0,0,,directly with Metal?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.31,0:25:57.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Enter SKRenderer.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.03,0:26:02.03,Default,,0,0,0,,You use it instead of SKView to
Dialogue: 0,0:26:02.03,0:26:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,gain more control over
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.20,0:26:03.87,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.69,0:26:07.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Like SKView, to use it you just
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.99,0:26:09.93,Default,,0,0,0,,set it your scene -- you set
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.93,0:26:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,your scene on it on the
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.88,0:26:11.24,Default,,0,0,0,,renderer.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:11.89,0:26:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Unlike SKView however,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.53,0:26:15.03,Default,,0,0,0,,SKRenderer let's you determine
Dialogue: 0,0:26:15.03,0:26:16.59,Default,,0,0,0,,when SpriteKit performs updating
Dialogue: 0,0:26:16.59,0:26:17.18,Default,,0,0,0,,and rendering.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.14,0:26:19.33,Default,,0,0,0,,It allows you to work directly
Dialogue: 0,0:26:19.33,0:26:20.96,Default,,0,0,0,,with Metal and then you can do
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.96,0:26:22.33,Default,,0,0,0,,things like render SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.33,0:26:23.44,Default,,0,0,0,,into an off screen texture to
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.66,0:26:24.53,Default,,0,0,0,,use however you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.47,0:26:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,This by the way is how SceneKit
Dialogue: 0,0:26:26.96,0:26:28.60,Default,,0,0,0,,is able to efficiently render
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.60,0:26:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content in 3D.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.39,0:26:32.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It uses SKRenderer under the
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.97,0:26:33.09,Default,,0,0,0,,hood.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.72,0:26:36.49,Default,,0,0,0,,There are four stages to using
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.56,0:26:38.67,Default,,0,0,0,,SKRenderer -- initialization,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.14,0:26:41.76,Default,,0,0,0,,setting the scene, updating, and
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.76,0:26:42.12,Default,,0,0,0,,rendering.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.30,0:26:44.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Initialization occurs once.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.26,0:26:46.41,Default,,0,0,0,,You set your scene at the start
Dialogue: 0,0:26:46.41,0:26:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,and again we want the transition
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.52,0:26:49.67,Default,,0,0,0,,to a new scene and update and
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.67,0:26:51.39,Default,,0,0,0,,renderer repeat every frame in
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.39,0:26:51.63,Default,,0,0,0,,your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.63,0:26:54.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's look at some code for each
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.71,0:26:57.42,Default,,0,0,0,,of these stages.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.51,0:26:59.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Stage one Initialization.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.76,0:27:01.80,Default,,0,0,0,,To initialize SKRenderer, all
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.80,0:27:02.72,Default,,0,0,0,,you need to do is provide it
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.84,0:27:05.91,Default,,0,0,0,,with a Metal device.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.66,0:27:08.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Stage Two, setting the scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.35,0:27:10.56,Default,,0,0,0,,This works exactly the same as
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.56,0:27:12.08,Default,,0,0,0,,with SKView, just that your
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.08,0:27:13.73,Default,,0,0,0,,scene on SKRenderer's scene
Dialogue: 0,0:27:13.73,0:27:14.12,Default,,0,0,0,,property.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:17.38,0:27:18.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Stage Three, updating.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.60,0:27:21.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Also very simple, all you need
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.10,0:27:23.39,Default,,0,0,0,,to do is pass in the current
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.18,0:27:25.29,Default,,0,0,0,,time.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.81,0:27:27.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Stage four, rendering.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.78,0:27:28.68,Default,,0,0,0,,This is done by calling the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.68,0:27:29.79,Default,,0,0,0,,render method of which there are
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.79,0:27:30.52,Default,,0,0,0,,two flavors.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:31.27,0:27:32.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Which one you want to use is
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.33,0:27:33.45,Default,,0,0,0,,situational, depending on how
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.45,0:27:34.78,Default,,0,0,0,,you want to use your SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:27:34.78,0:27:35.82,Default,,0,0,0,,content with Metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.51,0:27:39.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Both methods ask you to specify
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.38,0:27:40.47,Default,,0,0,0,,your viewport you like to render
Dialogue: 0,0:27:40.47,0:27:42.11,Default,,0,0,0,,into, which is just the CGrect
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.15,0:27:43.08,Default,,0,0,0,,that defines the area of
Dialogue: 0,0:27:43.08,0:27:45.03,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit will draw into in the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.03,0:27:48.46,Default,,0,0,0,,render target.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.30,0:27:50.89,Default,,0,0,0,,And they both take a Metal
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.89,0:27:51.99,Default,,0,0,0,,render pass descriptor, which
Dialogue: 0,0:27:51.99,0:27:53.27,Default,,0,0,0,,describes that render target
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.27,0:27:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,that you want the SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.48,0:27:58.62,Default,,0,0,0,,content to draw into.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.08,0:28:00.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Now the first method allows you
Dialogue: 0,0:28:00.25,0:28:01.99,Default,,0,0,0,,to specify the command buffer to
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.99,0:28:03.35,Default,,0,0,0,,which SpriteKit will schedule
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.58,0:28:04.38,Default,,0,0,0,,rendering commands.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.40,0:28:06.44,Default,,0,0,0,,A good case in which to call
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.44,0:28:07.37,Default,,0,0,0,,this method is if you're not
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.45,0:28:08.96,Default,,0,0,0,,directly mixing SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:28:08.96,0:28:10.73,Default,,0,0,0,,content with other Metal content
Dialogue: 0,0:28:10.85,0:28:11.97,Default,,0,0,0,,in the same render target.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.58,0:28:13.65,Default,,0,0,0,,If you want to render a
Dialogue: 0,0:28:13.65,0:28:15.09,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit scene into a texture
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.09,0:28:16.18,Default,,0,0,0,,and then apply it through some
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.18,0:28:17.85,Default,,0,0,0,,3D geometry like we did in the
Dialogue: 0,0:28:17.85,0:28:19.20,Default,,0,0,0,,second demo we showed you this
Dialogue: 0,0:28:19.41,0:28:20.33,Default,,0,0,0,,is the method you'd want to
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.33,0:28:20.56,Default,,0,0,0,,call.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:23.20,0:28:25.28,Default,,0,0,0,,The second method gives you more
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.28,0:28:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,granularity by allowing you to
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.66,0:28:28.96,Default,,0,0,0,,direct which render command
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.96,0:28:30.52,Default,,0,0,0,,encoder SpriteKit will encode
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.57,0:28:31.36,Default,,0,0,0,,its render commands.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:31.89,0:28:33.14,Default,,0,0,0,,This is good if you want to
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.14,0:28:34.49,Default,,0,0,0,,directly mix SpriteKit and metal
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.49,0:28:35.97,Default,,0,0,0,,content in the same render
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.97,0:28:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,target.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:36.94,0:28:38.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So you want to render some 2D
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.33,0:28:39.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Metal content along with your
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.64,0:28:41.27,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content or maybe you
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.27,0:28:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,want to overlay SpriteKit on top
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.04,0:28:44.46,Default,,0,0,0,,of a Metal scene to display HUD
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.46,0:28:44.97,Default,,0,0,0,,elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.71,0:28:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,By using the same render command
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.12,0:28:48.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and coder, you can do this much
Dialogue: 0,0:28:48.44,0:28:49.37,Default,,0,0,0,,more efficiently than if you
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.37,0:28:50.38,Default,,0,0,0,,were using the first method.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:50.38,0:28:54.36,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, that's enough of an
Dialogue: 0,0:28:54.36,0:28:55.08,Default,,0,0,0,,API crawl.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.35,0:28:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's jump into a quick demo
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.29,0:28:57.37,Default,,0,0,0,,showing SpriteKit rendering in
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.37,0:28:59.99,Default,,0,0,0,,3D with Metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.52,0:29:08.84,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.34,0:29:11.99,Default,,0,0,0,,SO here we have a 3D scene in
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.99,0:29:12.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:13.14,0:29:14.45,Default,,0,0,0,,See we've got some nice lighting
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.45,0:29:16.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and some shadows going on here
Dialogue: 0,0:29:16.94,0:29:18.25,Default,,0,0,0,,and we have this very tempting
Dialogue: 0,0:29:18.25,0:29:20.57,Default,,0,0,0,,looking arcade cabinet with our
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.87,0:29:22.18,Default,,0,0,0,,beautiful SpriteKit framework
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.18,0:29:22.77,Default,,0,0,0,,logo on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:23.90,0:29:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We walk up to it, Insert Coin,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.30,0:29:28.30,Default,,0,0,0,,that sounds like of tempting.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.30,0:29:29.08,Default,,0,0,0,,I've got a quarter here.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.08,0:29:30.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's plop that baby in.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.13,0:29:34.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, you see we've got a full
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.21,0:29:36.42,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit scene rendering on
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.85,0:29:38.79,Default,,0,0,0,,this 3D Metal scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:39.38,0:29:41.30,Default,,0,0,0,,And see we're using SKRenderer
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.67,0:29:43.47,Default,,0,0,0,,to render SpriteKit into a
Dialogue: 0,0:29:43.47,0:29:44.94,Default,,0,0,0,,texture, which we're then
Dialogue: 0,0:29:44.94,0:29:46.75,Default,,0,0,0,,mapping onto the front of our
Dialogue: 0,0:29:46.75,0:29:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,arcade cabinet here.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.91,0:29:49.96,Default,,0,0,0,,And then we're just applying a
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.96,0:29:53.12,Default,,0,0,0,,cool CRT shader to an in Metal
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.43,0:29:55.32,Default,,0,0,0,,to give it this old school look.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.38,0:29:57.17,Default,,0,0,0,,I can actually move around from
Dialogue: 0,0:29:57.17,0:29:58.52,Default,,0,0,0,,any angle I want to here and I
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.52,0:30:00.93,Default,,0,0,0,,can interact with it like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.05,0:30:01.81,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a little bit of askew, but
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.81,0:30:02.77,Default,,0,0,0,,you know, maybe this gives you
Dialogue: 0,0:30:02.77,0:30:04.21,Default,,0,0,0,,some memories of playing on an
Dialogue: 0,0:30:04.21,0:30:05.12,Default,,0,0,0,,arcade cabinet with your
Dialogue: 0,0:30:05.12,0:30:06.02,Default,,0,0,0,,friends, you're all crowded up
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.02,0:30:06.44,Default,,0,0,0,,against it.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.44,0:30:08.72,Default,,0,0,0,,And you can view this from any
Dialogue: 0,0:30:08.72,0:30:10.25,Default,,0,0,0,,angle, you can view this all
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.25,0:30:14.35,Default,,0,0,0,,from a distance, and it shows
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.35,0:30:15.84,Default,,0,0,0,,you some of the things that you
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.90,0:30:17.56,Default,,0,0,0,,can do with SpriteKit when you
Dialogue: 0,0:30:17.56,0:30:18.39,Default,,0,0,0,,use it with Metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:18.66,0:30:20.52,Default,,0,0,0,,It let's you use it 3D and then
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.52,0:30:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,you can do whatever you want
Dialogue: 0,0:30:21.68,0:30:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,with that texture.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.05,0:30:29.77,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's SpriteKit and Metal
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.86,0:30:30.46,Default,,0,0,0,,working together.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:31.52,0:30:35.78,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:30:36.28,0:30:37.45,Default,,0,0,0,,SKRenderer gives you more
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.45,0:30:38.94,Default,,0,0,0,,control over SpriteKit than ever
Dialogue: 0,0:30:38.94,0:30:39.37,Default,,0,0,0,,before.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:39.82,0:30:40.72,Default,,0,0,0,,It allows you to determine
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.72,0:30:41.96,Default,,0,0,0,,exactly when it updates and
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.96,0:30:43.39,Default,,0,0,0,,renders and by interacting
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.39,0:30:44.94,Default,,0,0,0,,directly with Metal you can use
Dialogue: 0,0:30:44.94,0:30:46.12,Default,,0,0,0,,rendered SpriteKit content
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.57,0:30:47.50,Default,,0,0,0,,anyway you see fit.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:50.85,0:30:52.07,Default,,0,0,0,,As you've seen today SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:30:52.07,0:30:54.09,Default,,0,0,0,,is useful in both 2D and 3D.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:54.90,0:30:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,It's built to work well with
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.98,0:30:57.22,Default,,0,0,0,,other graphics frameworks like
Dialogue: 0,0:30:57.22,0:30:58.44,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit and Metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.44,0:31:00.09,Default,,0,0,0,,And it's closely integrated with
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.09,0:31:01.27,Default,,0,0,0,,ARKit, so that creating
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.27,0:31:02.96,Default,,0,0,0,,augmented reality apps is as
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.06,0:31:04.23,Default,,0,0,0,,easy as possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.73,0:31:06.31,Default,,0,0,0,,We've introduced new features
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.31,0:31:07.59,Default,,0,0,0,,that give you more control than
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.59,0:31:08.83,Default,,0,0,0,,ever allowing you to view
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.83,0:31:09.92,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit content in the View
Dialogue: 0,0:31:09.92,0:31:11.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger and also giving you the
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.71,0:31:13.39,Default,,0,0,0,,ability to take direct control
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.39,0:31:14.65,Default,,0,0,0,,over when and how SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.65,0:31:15.88,Default,,0,0,0,,updates and renders with a new
Dialogue: 0,0:31:15.99,0:31:16.66,Default,,0,0,0,,SKRenderer.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.21,0:31:19.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Today we've shown SpriteKit in
Dialogue: 0,0:31:19.01,0:31:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,an entirely new light and we
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.16,0:31:21.23,Default,,0,0,0,,hope that it's given you some
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.43,0:31:23.04,Default,,0,0,0,,perspective on how you can use
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.04,0:31:24.17,Default,,0,0,0,,it in ways that you may have
Dialogue: 0,0:31:24.17,0:31:25.14,Default,,0,0,0,,never thought of before.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.78,0:31:28.76,Default,,0,0,0,,So for information and access to
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.76,0:31:29.92,Default,,0,0,0,,this session video please visit
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.01,0:31:34.25,Default,,0,0,0,,developer.apple.com/wwdc17/609.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.25,0:31:36.89,Default,,0,0,0,,And please check out these
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.89,0:31:37.74,Default,,0,0,0,,related sessions.
